<HEADLINE>
<P>
NIBBLES AND BITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Kenneth Williams 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Choreographer Pearl Primus, professor of ethnic studies at Amherst College in 
Massachusetts, has been named Chancellor's Distinguished Lecturer in Fine Arts 
at UC Irvine where she will begin a weeklong residency next Monday. Her 
lecture-demonstration on "Dance, Music and Related Arts of Africa" will be free 
to the public May 2 at 7:30 p.m. at the UCI Physical Sciences Lecture Hall. 
Born in Trinidad, Primas, 71, studied with such American modern dance pioneers 
as Martha Graham, Doris Humphrey, Hanya Holm and Charles Weidman and has 
performed her own choreography throughout the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Appointment 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA042390-0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 208443 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
April 23, 1990, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
50 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: THE NAME GAME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and international 
news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Entertainers and Their Original Names 
</P>
<P>
Michael Landon: Eugene Orowitz 
</P>
<P>
Dean Martin: Dino Crocetti 
</P>
<P>
Stefanie Powers: Zofja Federkiewicz 
</P>
<P>
Redd Foxx: John Sanford 
</P>
