<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIVE CREW'S 'NASTY' MAY BE CINCINNATI'S NEXT TARGET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHUCK PHILIPS and ALLAN PARACHINI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Hamilton County Sheriff's Department in Cincinnati has initiated an 
investigation to determine whether "As Nasty as They Want to Be," a sexually 
explicit album by the Miami-based rap group 2 Live Crew, violates obscenity 
codes in Ohio. The investigation was prompted by a complaint from Florida 
anti-obscenity crusader Jack Thompson, who faxed a transcription of six 2 Live 
Crew songs to Hamilton County Sheriff Simon Leis and to city police stations in 
Cincinnati and Dayton on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
"All I can say is that the matter is under investigation," said Frank Wiekel, 
director of relations for the Sheriff's Department. "The vice squad is looking 
into it and I would think that sometime (this) week we should be able to 
provide some sort of determination on it." 
</P>
<P>
The rap group's "Nasty" album has been declared obscene in four judicial 
circuits encompassing 13 counties in the state of Florida. The sexually 
explicit record has been deemed to violate obscenity codes in some counties in 
Indiana and Tennessee, while authorities in Pennsylvania and Washington have 
issued opinions declaring "Nasty" harmful to minors. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Assn. of Art Museum Directors, which represents 153 of the 
nation's largest art exhibition centers, will hold an emergency meeting of its 
board of directors at Cincinnati's Contemporary Arts Center today. The New 
York-based group said it would issue a statement after the special meeting, at 
which Dennis Barrie, the local center's director, is to appear as an invited 
guest. 
</P>
<P>
The association is headed by John Walsh, director of the J. Paul Getty Museum 
in Malibu, and was among the first establishment arts groups to take a strong 
position opposing restrictions on artistic freedom when last year's crisis over 
National Endowment for the Arts funding of controversial exhibits began. Walsh 
said the emergency board meeting had been called to "discuss what action should 
be taken by the directors of the nation's museums to defend First Amendment 
rights." CHUCK PHILIPS and ALLAN PARACHINI 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
OBSCENITY; CENSORSHIP; PORNOGRAPHY; 2 LIVE CREW (MUSIC GROUP); RAP MUSIC; ART 
-- UNITED STATES; ART -- OHIO 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
