<P>
GOLDIE HAWN LOOKS TO NEW CAREER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Goldie Hawn, the go-go dancer who turned a wide-eyed dumb blonde routine into a 
string of hit movies in the 1970s, is hoping to revitalize her career in the 
1990s. 
</P>
<P>
"I didn't become a movie star because I made people cry or because I had some 
incredible romantic persona," Hawn said in an interview in the May issue of 
Fame magazine. 
</P>
<P>
"I came on the scene with an effervescence and a lightness and an ability to 
elevate spirits, which, by the way, I do not sell short." 
</P>
<P>
After success with "Cactus Flower," "Shampoo," "Butterflies Are Free" and 
"Private Benjamin," she starred in a series of movies -- "Swing Shift," 
"Overboard" and others -- that she admits were disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
But Hawn, 44, has a slew of projects in the works, including a comedy with Mel 
Gibson, "Bird on a Wire," which opens next month, and a seven-film deal with 
Disney's Hollywood Pictures. 
</P>
