<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: WILL GARBO EX-PAL SAM GREEN PLEASE STAND UP? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THIS COLUMN has been trying to find Garbo's former pal Sam Green. They were 
very close until the actress discovered that Sam had been taping their 
conversations. Sam, if you read this, give a call. 
</P>
<P>
R. G. Friedman of Brooklyn asks: "How did Garbo manage to live comfortably 
without doing any kind of work, no movies in nearly 50 years?" Good question. 
Well, Garbo was notoriously close with a dollar. There are no notable acts of 
charity or generosity in her life. She herself lived rather simply. She often 
visited and traveled as "the world's guest," notably aboard the yacht of her 
friend, the Baroness Cecile de Rothschild. (She is now very ill in Paris.) 
</P>
<P>
A typical Garbo incident occurred in Greece when the star was visiting a member 
of the Calliga shipping family. After a long stay, she left behind a rueful 
maid who had attended her. The maid liked to show off the old straw hat with 
its holes and frayed edges, saying, "Garbo gave me this; it was her tip!" 
</P>
<P>
Garbo invested early in the 1930s in valuable Los Angeles real estate, which 
has only gone up and up ever since. She has likely left a sizable fortune. 
</P>
<P>
THE MANNER in which ABC's "PrimeTime" offered up its background to the Marla 
Maples interview -- why, my, my -- out there in TV-land, I'm sure the public 
got the idea that the New York Post was the newspaper that scooped and covered 
the big story of the Ivana-Donald Trump split. Diane Sawyer's producers didn't 
even bother to show you the New York Daily News front page that busted this one 
wide open. 
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON has always been such a "company town" its business is "government" 
and "gossip." So public figures in D.C. always concentrate a lot on image. 
</P>
<P>
But the TV age has now arrived with such a vengeance that every congressman, 
senator and Cabinet member knows enough to want a good makeup before going on 
the air. Some now arrive at studios with makeup charts, outlining their 
best/worst features, numbers and brand names of foundation bases, etc. One of 
the most dedicated is West Virginia's Sen. Jay Rockefeller. 
</P>
<P>
ANYBODY AROUND here care that Eddie Murphy's enormous exclusive contract with 
Paramount has ended? Every studio has, of course, offered him a blank check to 
relocate. But Eddie says he needs to take some time off. He is spending it in a 
very Bill Cosby-ish way, with his new baby daughter at his house in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
NOW THAT David Geffen has bought the nine-acre Jack Warner estate in Beverly 
Hills for a record $47.5 million, let's note he also bought a screenplay by 
Shane "Lethal Weapon" Black for a record $1.75 million. "The Last Boy Scout" 
was a sizzling property, the center of an auction frenzy by the majors. 
</P>
<P>
Geffen, with his $500-million profits from the sale of his record company to 
MCA safely tucked away, is also ready to bring the Broadway musical 
"Dreamgirls" to the screen. 
</P>
<P>
There is continuing speculation that Spike Lee will direct. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Greta Garbo in her trademark straw hat in 1985. Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
